{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564838"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:18:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:18:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17142"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627672"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:50:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:50:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17142"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17142"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.78,0.12,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9832"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68607"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9832"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17142"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54064"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"1440"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"10724"},{"type":"tags","id":"11157"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23012"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68607"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic for advice following his parent\u0027s recent diagnosis of familial adenomatous polyposis. His parent was diagnosed after investigation of rectal bleeding, and genetic testing confirmed an APC gene mutation. The boy has no symptoms and no significant medical history. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Fundoscopy reveals multiple hyperpigmented retinal lesions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely mode of inheritance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["X-linked recessive","Autosomal dominant","Autosomal recessive","X-linked dominant","Mitochondrial"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a family history of familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP). The pattern of inheritance and clinical features are characteristic of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eautosomal dominant\u003C/strong\u003E condition. This is confirmed by the presence of an APC gene mutation, which follows autosomal dominant inheritance with nearly 100% penetrance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked recessive\u003C/strong\u003E inheritance would typically show affected males with carrier females, and transmission would not occur from father to son. This pattern is not consistent with FAP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutosomal recessive\u003C/strong\u003E inheritance would require both parents to be carriers, and siblings would have a 25% chance of being affected. This is not the pattern seen in FAP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked dominant\u003C/strong\u003E conditions typically affect females more severely than males and show no male-to-male transmission. This is not consistent with FAP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitochondrial\u003C/strong\u003E inheritance is characterised by maternal transmission only, with all offspring of affected mothers being at risk. This is not the pattern seen in FAP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the inheritance pattern is crucial for genetic counselling and risk assessment. In FAP, first-degree relatives have a 50% chance of inheriting the mutation. The presence of congenital hypertrophy of retinal pigment epithelium (CHRPE) in this patient is a characteristic extracolonic manifestation of FAP, though genetic testing is required for definitive diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Familial adenomatous polyposis is inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern with high penetrance.","Extracolonic manifestations of FAP include duodenal polyps, desmoid tumours, and congenital hypertrophy of retinal pigment epithelium.","First-degree relatives of FAP patients should undergo genetic testing and colonoscopy screening starting from age 12-14 years."],"references":["Yen T, Stanich PP, Axell L, Patel SG. APC-Associated Polyposis Conditions. In: Adam MP, Feldman J, Mirzaa GM, Pagon RA, Wallace SE, Amemiya A, editors. GeneReviews\u00ae [Internet]. Seattle (WA): University of Washington, Seattle; 1993 [cited 2024 Dec 9]. Available from: http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK1345/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54064"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17142"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54064"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T22:48:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T22:50:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9832"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68607"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"descriptio